    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="NA217-kiḷavi">itu talaimakaḷ vāyiṉ maṟuttatu.</p>
        <p xml:lang="en">This is who SHE refused the door.</p>
      </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="NA217">
<l>            icaipaṭa vāḻpavar celvam pōlak</l>
<l>            kāṇṭoṟum poliyuṅ kataḻvāy vēḻa</l>
<l>            miruṅkēḻ vayappuli verīi yayalatu</l>
<l>            karuṅkāl vēṅkai yūṟupaṭa maṟalip</l>
<l>            peruñciṉan taṇiyuṅ kuṉṟa nāṭa </l>
<l>            ṉaṉiperi tiṉiya ṉāyiṉun tuṉipaṭarn</l>
<l>            tūṭa luṟuvēṉ ṟōḻi nīṭu</l>
<l>            pulampucē ṇakala nīntip</l>
<l>            pulavi yuṇartal vaṇmai yāṉē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg xml:lang="en">
<l rend="indent2">The man from the hilly land,</l>
<l rend="indent">where, being frightened by big lustrous strong tiger, after giving fight,</l>
<l rend="indent2">as it happened to be in the way, to the flame-like Vēṅkai tree nearby,</l>
<l rend="indent">the great anger subsides in the quick-trunked(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kataḻvāy</term>, literally a "hastening mouth", might refer to the elephant’s skill in moving its trunk. T.V.G. takes <term xml:lang="ta">vāy</term> as "area" here and explains the whole as "quick gait", which is not convincing. Another aspect might be transmissional error: ET reads kataḻ varal here, "of quick coming", a verbal noun being likewise not the most desirable kind of attribute, but it does away with the <term xml:lang="ta">vāy</term>. By the way, the rest of the elephant description, too, sounds a little bit strange.</note> elephant bull,</l>
<l rend="indent2">welling up whenever it sees [its enemy],<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kāṇ-toṟum poliyum</term>: although positioned quite far off I suggest to take this as a further description of the elephant’s <term xml:lang="ta">ciṉam</term>.</note> </l>
<l rend="indent2">as the prosperity of those who live to acquire fame,</l>
<l rend="indent2">– even if he [is] very very pleasing, thinking of disgust</l>
<l>I will quarrel [with him], friend,</l>
<l rend="indent2">so that he realises to the full(?)<note place="foot">How to integrate <term xml:lang="ta">vaṇmaiyāṉ</term>? Vexation in all its bounty?</note> [my] vexation</l>
<l rend="indent2">[and] crosses the distant width of prolonged loneliness.</l>
<lg type="alternate" sameAs="4b">
    <l>after giving fight to the ... Vēṅkai tree so that [its trunk] oozes</l>
</lg>
<lg type="alternate" sameAs="9B">
    <l>to make [him] realise to the full [my] vexation</l>
</lg>
<lg type="alternate" sameAs="9C">
    <l>to make [him] pacify to the full [my] vexation<note place="foot">This is the version chosen by T.V.G.: the woman picking up a love quarrel to have the pleasure of seeing HIM pacify her, a well-known topos certainly from Prākrit poetry as well as later Tamil poetry (for example the <term xml:lang="ta">Kuṟaḷ</term>), but not so openly existent in the early Tamil anthologies.</note></l>
</lg>
        </lg>
      </div>
